 the Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in England</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, on reducing unnecessary regulatory burdens, and on ways to deliver even better levels of compliance. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> A number of respondents </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">criticised</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the provisions of Part P </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of the Regulations </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">electrical safety</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">citing t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he cost and bureaucracy </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">they</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> imposed on insta</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">llers, building control bodies and consumers. In the light of these concerns</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">then </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Building Regulations Minister, Andrew Stunell, announced in December 2010 that Part P was to be included in a programme of work to develop proposals for consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">changes to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government consulted on changes to Part P in January 2012</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> announced its conclusions in December 2012</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Notwithstanding the criticisms of Part P, the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> announced that</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Part P would be retained, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">but with a reduction in the scope of notifiable work and with the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">third</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">party certification as an alternative route to demonstrating compliance. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The changes to Part P came into force on 6 April 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a revised version of Approved Document P </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Electrical safety – Dwellings</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">was issued, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> statutory guidance on how to comply with this part of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">egulations</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> guidance set out the principles of third party certification but no schemes were avail</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">able at that time.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In October 2013 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Department </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">invited applications </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">from bodies wishing to operate third</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">party certification schemes for electrical installations in dwellings</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  The intention is to introduce these new schemes early in 2014.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  This will be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">done by way of an amendment to the Regulations, to name any schemes which are authorised.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As part of the programme of review of Building Regulations, the Department issued new conditions of authorisation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">competent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> person</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> schemes </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n June 2012</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  An important new condition was that all schemes would have to achieve accreditation by the UK Accreditation Service (UKAS) against the standard </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BS </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">EN 45011 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">General requirements for bodies operating product certification systems</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by June 2014</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There are a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lso new conditions about the way scheme operators are to assess the competence of their registrants against National Occupational Standards and to undertake ongoing surveillance of their work.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Response to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ommittee’s </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify